        <Document ID="04DCB718-D44B-4BD5-ABAE-0EB6F2941555">
            <Title>2C: WHAT IF + DABBLING IN LOVE</Title>
            <Text>2C: WHAT IF + DABBLING IN LOVE

No matter what they are, excuses are still only excuses. Because C1 and C2 are spending so much time together and things are going so well, their excuses are being attacked. This should be the first time they start thinking “what if” instead of “absolutely not”, although they still have a long way to go before their excuses are destroyed and existing problems are solved.

Something needs to trigger the “what if”, and it can be an intimate moment spent together or some kind of a good deed that makes C1 see C2 in a different light, and/or vice versa. Maybe C2 remembered how C1 mentioned they really like chocolate chip cookies so C2 goes to a cooking class to learn how to bake, or maybe C1 finds out C2 missed out on a job interview to help C1 with moving. It should be obvious to your readers why these two belong together.

It’s now impossible not to have those fluttery feelings and lingering gazes, and your characters are pretty much teetering on the edge of falling in love for real. Depending on what type of romance you’re writing, C1 and C2 could even end up in bed together. (If they’ve already slept with each other casually, this time it’s with feeling.) It’s looking like it could perhaps work after all, but don’t forget, they still need to be working towards their external goals too.
</Text>
