            <Title>1C: MAKING EXCUSES + A NEW EXTERNAL GOAL</Title>
            <Text>1C: MAKING EXCUSES + A NEW EXTERNAL GOAL
A romance novel is going to need a lot of ups and downs, or should we say, going towards each other and pulling away from each other. C2 might already be pursuing C1, but C1 should be adamant that they’re not going to have a relationship with this person even if they are attracted to each other. 

The existing problems you introduced in Normal World are the reason behind these excuses and your character needs to deal with them before their happy ending. Maybe they think being in a relationship would require them to change their personality, maybe they feel inadequate about their lack of formal education or maybe they think you can’t have a successful career as an author when you’re married. Be creative and make the excuse based on something that has happened to the character in the past.

Since everything in the outer layer of the story has also changed, there needs to be a new goal that has to do with solving the external problem. This goal could also be a reason why C1 is refusing to see that C2 is what they need.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="B425FBFC-5787-4AB1-A985-A7711383C291">
            <Title>3A: PULLING AWAY</Title>
            <Text>3A: PULLING AWAY
This is the beginning of the third quarter of your story. Your characters should become more proactive in trying to reach their external goals instead of just reacting, but they’re still doing things the wrong way and letting their weaknesses take the wheel. C1 and C2 are retreating from each other because of their fears and misconceptions.

Remember what I said earlier about going towards each other and then pulling away? Now is the time to pull away again. The “victory” you just wrote about really was false after all because C1 and C2 still have loads of issues they haven’t dealt with and they haven’t learned their lessons yet. 

Your characters have dabbled in love but they’re not yet ready to take the plunge - something is making them feel like chickening out would be the better option. Remember those excuses they made earlier on? Now is the time for them to think those excuses actually are valid reasons that are based on rational thinking. If C1 has always thought they can’t be in a relationship because they’re so eccentric, perhaps C2’s mother makes them feel like a weirdo. Attack their soft spots and make them think they’ve been utter fools for ever thinking this could work - and don’t be too nice.

With your outer layer of the story, things should also be going pretty badly. This is generally a pretty tense part of the story and you shouldn’t be too easy on your characters.

Continue making things even worse for C1 and C2.  Their doubts about the relationship should be getting bigger even if they’re pretending that nothing’s wrong. They should be looking for signs that prove that their excuses were totally valid and that they were right all along to avoid love.
</Text>
        </Document>
