        <Document ID="57397F1F-7B68-4CEB-9FEE-B5A6C09BB47E">
            <Title>4A: THE CONSEQUENCES + THE REALISATION</Title>
            <Text>4A: THE CONSEQUENCES + THE REALISATION
This is the beginning of your final quarter. Here all the loose ends are tied and problems get solved because your characters learned their lessons and learned to look past their misconceptions.

Your characters have made their choices and they think they should be feeling better about it, but unfortunately, they actually feel pretty rubbish. They remember all the good times they had during New World, Old Problems and they can’t help but realise they’re responsible for what has now happened.

Remember that new character you introduced who has something to do with the lesson that your character needs to learn? Here’s a great place for them to tell your character what a big dum-dum they really are. Things are about to change, but make sure your characters really wallow first.

After wallowing, it becomes obvious that something needs to be done. It’s time to stop being an idiot and finally do something to fix things (which happens next). They have nothing left to lose so they have no other choice but to act even if it requires a whole new level of being vulnerable.
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="6C55DF2B-C9B9-48A1-942A-F50FCC864463">
            <Title>4C: CLOSING IMAGE AND THE NEW NORMAL</Title>
            <Text>4C: CLOSING IMAGE AND THE NEW NORMAL
The lovers have now been united and all the problems are behind them. Everything in the outer layer of the story has been nicely tied up as well and all there is to do is to show what the New Normal is like. 

To add more meaning to this final scene, you could mirror the beginning of the story, for example the very first scene or the scene where C1 and C2 met. Give your readers enough so that they can be satisfied with the information but end the story sooner rather than later. Include an epilogue if you’d like.
</Text>
